thread.title: 24 French Baby Names That'll Make You Want To Have Children
thread.title_full: 24 French Baby Names That'll Make You Want To Have Children

author: Marie Telling
title: 24 French Baby Names That'll Make You Want To Have Children
text:
View this image ›
onebluelight / Getty Images Camille is a very popular gender-neutral name of latin origin.
ID: 10332013 2. Maël/Maëlle View this image ›
nitimongkolchai / Getty Images Maël (Maëlle, for girls) is an old name from Brittany that means “prince.”
ID: 10332055 3. Marcel View this image ›
AGrigorjeva / Getty Images Marcel comes from the latin word “marcus” which means “dedicated to the god Mars.”
ID: 10332098 4. Chloé View this image ›
Getty Images One of the most popular names in France thanks to the book Froth on the Daydream , whose heroine is named Chloé. The name comes from the Greek and was another name given to Demeter, the goddess of the harvest.
ID: 10332014 5. Manon View this image ›
ozgurdonmaz / Getty Images Like Marie, Manon comes from the Hebrew name Myriam. It’s the name of the character played by Emmanuelle Béart in Manon of the Spring , a 1986 critically acclaimed movie.
ID: 10332032 6. Margaux View this image ›
szefei / Getty Images Like the name Margaret, Margaux comes the latin “margarita” which means “pearl.”
ID: 10332035 7. Daphné View this image ›
Getty Images Daphné comes from the Greek “daphnê” which means “laurels.”
ID: 10332864 8. Erwan View this image ›
monkeybusinessimages / Getty Images Another name from Brittany. Erwan comes from the celtic word “aerouant” which means “dragon.”
ID: 10332069 9. Océane View this image ›
Bodler / gettyimages.com Océane comes from “océan,” which means ocean in French. It’s been a popular girl name in France since the 90s.
ID: 10332080 10. Gaël/Gaëlle View this image ›
FamVeld / Getty Images Gaël, and its feminine counterpart Gaëlle, is another Celtic name from Brittany that’s very popular in France.
ID: 10332070 11. Céleste View this image ›
AGrigorjeva / Getty Images Céleste means celestial in French.
ID: 10332081 12. Delphine View this image ›
Getty Images Delphine comes from the Latin “delphinus” which means “dolphin.”
ID: 10332849 13. Anaïs View this image ›
GeorgeRudy / Getty Images Anaïs is derived from “Hannah,” which means grace in Hebrew. It’s also the name of literary legend, Anaïs Nin.
ID: 10332012 14. Anouk View this image ›
DONOT6 / Getty Images Anouk comes from the Hebrew name “Hannah” which means “grace.” It’s the name of famous French actress Anouk Aimée, who played in A Man and A Woman and 8½ .
ID: 10332087 15. Lou View this image ›
Getty Images While it’s mostly a boy name in the US, Lou is a girl name in France. Like Louis, it comes from the german Hludowig and means “glory” and “fight.”
ID: 10332089 16. Noé View this image ›
FamVeld / Getty Images Noé is the French version of Noah. Like its English counterpart, Noé comes from the Hebrew name “Noach” which means “rest” and “comfort.”
ID: 10332088 17. Joséphine View this image ›
HanyBahgat / Getty Images Joséphine is the feminine form of Joseph.
ID: 10332091 18. Alizée View this image ›
FamVeld / Getty Images Alizée comes from the name of a tropical wind called “Alizé.”
ID: 10332096 19. Raphaël View this image ›
katrinaelena / Getty Images Raphaël means “God heals” in Hebrew.
ID: 10332058 20. Nolwenn View this image ›
Denniro / Getty Images This girl name is another popular baby name from Brittany.
ID: 10332077 21. Émile View this image ›
GeorgeRudy / Getty Images Émile comes from the latin “aemelus” which means “rival.” It is the name of famous French writer, Émile Zola.
ID: 10332105 22. Capucine View this image ›
shironosov / Getty Images Capucine is a beautiful old French name and the name of a pretty flower called Tropaeolum majus in English.
ID: 10332109 23. Gaspard View this image ›
AGrigorjeva / Getty Images An old school French name that’s become trendy again over the past few years, Gaspard is the name of one of the Three Wise Men who are said to have visited Jesus after his birth.
ID: 10332114 24. Clémence View this image ›
Getty Images Clémence comes from the Latin “clemens” which means “merciful” and “kind.”
ID: 10332106
